Let H be the symmetric second-order differential operator on L2(R) with domain $${C_c^\infty({ f R})}$$ and action $${H\varphi=-(c\,\varphi^{\prime})^{\prime}}$$ where $${ c\in W^{1,2}_{m loc}({ f R})}$$ is a real function that is strictly positive on $${{ f R} ackslash\{0\}}$$ but with c(0) = 0. We give a complete characterization of the self-adjoint extensions and the submarkovian extensions of H. In particular if $${
u=
u_+\vee
u_-}$$ where $${
u_\pm(x)=\pm\int^{\pm 1}_{\pm x} c^{-1}}$$ then H has a unique self-adjoint extension if and only if $${
u
ot\in L_2(0,1)}$$ and a unique submarkovian extension if and only if $${
u
ot\in L_\infty(0,1)}$$. In both cases, the corresponding semigroup leaves L2(0,∞) and L2(−∞,0) invariant. In addition, we prove that for a general non-negative $${ c\in W^{1,\infty}_{m loc}({ f R})}$$ the corresponding operator H has a unique submarkovian extension.
